03222nam  2200457 i 20150219075040.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||150210s2015    miu      b    001 0beng    a2014032713  a9780472119493  a0472119494  a97804721207347 a10.3998/mpub.7277925  aMiUbengcMiU  ae-it---04aDG737.28.D39bC72 201500a945/.51105092aB2231 aCrabb, Ann,d1940-14aThe merchant of Prato's wife :bMargherita Datini and her world, 1360-1423 /cAnn Morton Crabb. 1aAnn Arbor :bThe University of Michigan Press,c2015.  a1 online resource (275 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier2 a"Although the fourteenth-century Italian merchant Francesco Datini has received attention from business historians, there has previously been no full study of his wife, Margherita Datini. Drawing on a sizable trove of Margherita's correspondence held in the Archivio di Stato di Prato, including hundreds of letters she exchanged with Francesco, Ann Crabb investigates the social and economic importance of women's roles as wives and mothers, early modern European views on honor, and the practice of letter writing in Margherita's world. Margherita's often colorful comments demonstrate her attitudes toward her rather unhappy marriage and her inability to have children, along with other aspects of her life. Her letters reveal the pride she felt in carrying out her many responsibilities as a wife and, later, a widow: in scribal letter writing, in business, in household management, and in farming. Crabb emphasizes that the role of a wife was a recognized social position, beyond her individual relations with her husband, and provided opportunities beyond what restrictive laws or restrictive views of female honor would suggest. Further, Crabb considers Margherita's successful efforts, on her own initiative and in her late thirties, to learn to read and write at a literate level. This book will be of interest to both scholars and general readers of women's history. In addition, historians of early modern Italy and, more generally, of early modern Europe will find this book valuable"--cProvided by publisher.  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.  aDescription based on information from the publisher.10aDatini, Margherita.10aDatini, MargheritaxMarriage.10aDatini, MargheritavCorrespondence.10aDatini, Francesco,d1335-1410. 0aWomenzItalyzFlorencevBiography. 0aWiveszItalyzFlorencevBiography. 0aFlorence (Italy)xHistoryyTo 1421. 0aLetter writingzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aFlorence (Italy)xSocial life and customs. 0aFlorence (Italy)vBiography. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.7277925